Title: The Raven
Credit: Screenplay adaptation of
Author: Edgar Allan Poe's poem (1845, public domain)
Draft date: 7/18/2026
Notes: Poem-to-screenplay test -- unusual formatting, minimal cast, single location. Paraphrased adaptation; does not reproduce the poem's verse.

====

FADE IN:

INT. CHAMBER - MIDNIGHT

A dim, book-lined study. Dying embers cast strange shadows on the floor. A MAN (30s, unshaven, grieving) sits slumped over a stack of old volumes, fighting sleep near the end of a long, bitter December night.

MAN (V.O.)
(weary, half to himself)
It was very late, and I was tired of reading, tired of trying not to think about her.

A soft, deliberate KNOCK sounds at the chamber door. The Man startles upright, unsure if he imagined it.

MAN
(muttering)
Only someone at the door. Nothing more than that.

He rises, crosses to the door, opens it onto an empty, dark hallway.

MAN (CONT'D)
(into the darkness, hopeful despite himself)
Lenore?

Only silence answers. He closes the door, unsettled, and returns to his chair.

A second, louder tapping -- this time at the window.

He throws open the shutter. A large, black RAVEN sweeps in past him without hesitation, and perches directly above the chamber door on a pale marble bust.

The Man stares at the bird, half-amused despite his grief.

MAN (CONT'D)
(to the raven, dry)
Well. You look like you came from somewhere far darker than my garden. Do you have a name?

RAVEN
(flat, croaking)
Nevermore.

The Man blinks, startled by the response, though he tells himself the word means nothing -- just noise a trained bird might repeat.

MAN (V.O.)
I told myself it was only a word the creature had picked up from some unlucky owner, repeated without sense or memory behind it.

He settles into a velvet chair directly beneath the bird, studying it, his grief for his lost love LENORE rising unbidden.

MAN (CONT'D)
(quietly, to himself)
Everyone else has left me eventually. I suppose you'll go too, in the morning, the same as the rest of what I hoped for.

RAVEN
Nevermore.

The Man startles at how precisely the bird's answer seems to fit his own thought, though he still tries to reason it away as coincidence.

MAN (CONT'D)
(leaning close, desperate)
Then tell me there's something that will let me stop grieving her. Some kind of relief -- even a small one.

RAVEN
Nevermore.

MAN (CONT'D)
(rising, anguished)
Then answer me honestly, whatever you are -- is there any comfort waiting for me anywhere at all?

RAVEN
Nevermore.

MAN (CONT'D)
(nearly shouting)
Will I see her again? Somewhere after all this -- will I hold her again?

RAVEN
Nevermore.

The Man staggers back, all composure gone.

MAN
(screaming)
Then get out! Take that single word and go back to wherever sent you -- leave me alone with what's left of this!

The Raven does not stir. It remains perched, unmoving, upon the pale bust above the chamber door, its shadow falling long across the floor.

The Man sinks back into his chair beneath it, defeated, the firelight dying around him.

MAN (V.O.)
(quiet, hollow)
And it never did leave. It's still there, some nights, when I close my eyes. And I understand, now, that whatever peace I was hoping for isn't coming -- not now, maybe not ever.

The embers go dark. Only the shape of the bird remains visible against the last grey light.

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
